## What happened

Apple removed DSA from its native cryptographic frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit). Starting in **.NET 7**, `DSA.Create()` throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS** because the runtime no longer has a platform provider for DSA there. It worked in .NET 10 only if your build was still targeting an older TFM or using a compatibility shim — the .NET 11 upgrade likely aligned you with the current behavior.

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not generate new ones), you have two practical options:

**Option 1 – Use BouncyCastle (recommended)**

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

public static bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] publicKeyBytes, byte[] data, byte[] signature)
{
    var keyParam = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);
    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA");
    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, keyParam);
    verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

This is pure managed code — works on all platforms with no native dependency.

**Option 2 – Guard with a runtime check**

If you want to keep using the built-in `DSA` class on Windows/Linux and only fall back on macOS:

```csharp
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;

if (!RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.OSX))
{
    using var dsa = DSA.Create();
    // ... use built-in API
}
else
{
    // BouncyCastle fallback
}
```

**Recommendation:** Go with **Option 1** (BouncyCastle everywhere). It removes platform-specific branching and keeps behavior consistent across all three OSes.
